@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xiii) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it REASSIGNS a mutable binding (`let mut x = 1` then `x = x + 5`).
-- eval mutates the binding in its environment; the compute spine lowers a `let` to a JS
-- `const` and has no reassignment statement — `block`'s `SBind` refuses a non-declaring
-- (reassigning) bind. The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN
-- refusal at the compiler frontier — never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s — clause dispatch over the
-- parameter patterns (see compile_multiclause_test). The frontier now sits at REASSIGNMENT
-- of a mutable binding. This file reassigns one, so it still refuses; when mutable `let`
-- lowers (a later D1 slice, a JS `let` + assignment), it flips from `unsupported` to a
-- print with no edit.

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let mut x = 1
  x = x + 5
  println(x)
